Why?

When you create an object from a class, you can normally change its attributes:

class Student:
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name

s = Student("John")
s.name = "Mike"    # Allowed

Since the object's state can be changed, it is mutable.

User-defined data structures in Python are generally mutable by default. They become immutable only when the programmer explicitly restricts modifications (e.g., using frozen dataclasses or read-only designs).
